Let's just say we're getting a crash course in hot weather alpaca
care. &lt;g&gt;

Actually, the breeder kindly spent about two hours with us, giving us
pointers, showing us how to trim hooves, discussing deworming, etc. We
loaded up two yearling alpacas into the back of the minivan and they
milled about for 20 minutes or so and then--for the most part--settled
down for the ride. Talkative little critters.

We unloaded them without fuss and we led the pony into her stall. She
was fascinated by the new critters. The big horses sniffed and whuffed
from the barn gate. The alpacas moved from one horse to the other
horse to the pony and generally everyone indulged in a long round of
sniffing. My mare decided that the alpacas weren't good for eating and
promptly lost interest. The gelding thinks that maybe these could be
play-toys.

Over the past days the alpacas have gotten friendly with the pony,
which is good because the plan is to put them in the 1/2 acre field
with her. When something disturbs them, they gather by her. They pull
hay out of her mouth. She nuzzles them. They nuzzle her. I'd describe
her attitude toward the alpacas as affectionate tolerance.

So, they've settled in nicely. Now if only this brutal, sweltering
heat wave would end...

--Karen Smith
